  <h1>What to Do After a Burn Injury</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by our editorial team. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>A serious burn injury changes everything &mdash; for the patient, the family, and the financial situation &mdash; in an instant. The decisions made in the first days and weeks have outsized impact on lifelong outcomes. This guide walks through the practical legal and financial steps that matter, with an honest acknowledgment that medical priorities come first and most of these steps can wait while immediate care is stabilized.</p>
  <p>This is informational only. Burn-injury cases require consultation with an experienced burn-injury attorney and care by verified burn-center specialists.</p>

  <h2>Step 1: Get to a verified burn center</h2>

  <p>The American Burn Association (ABA) maintains a list of verified burn centers &mdash; facilities that meet stringent criteria for burn-specific resources, staffing, and outcomes. ABA criteria for transfer to a verified burn center include:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Partial-thickness burns over 10% TBSA (5% in children).</li>
    <li>Any full-thickness burn.</li>
    <li>Burns to face, hands, feet, genitalia, perineum, or major joints.</li>
    <li>Electrical burns including lightning.</li>
    <li>Chemical burns.</li>
    <li>Inhalation injury.</li>
    <li>Burns in patients with significant pre-existing medical conditions.</li>
    <li>Burns in patients with concurrent trauma where the burn is the dominant injury.</li>
    <li>Burns in children at hospitals without pediatric burn capability.</li>
    <li>Burns in patients who will require special social, emotional, or rehabilitative intervention.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Verified burn centers have dramatically better outcomes than general hospitals for moderate-to-severe burns. If a hospital recommends keeping a significant burn case in-house rather than transferring, push back &mdash; the difference in long-term outcomes is documented and substantial. Insurance pushback against transfer is common in moderate burns; an attorney can help.</p>

  <h2>Step 2: Photograph the burn progression</h2>

  <p>Burn-injury cases turn heavily on visual evidence of severity and scar evolution. Family members can do this while medical care is the priority:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Initial photos in hospital</strong> &mdash; with date stamp, multiple angles. The acute appearance documents severity at admission.</li>
    <li><strong>Dressing-change photos</strong> &mdash; weekly or as the burn evolves. The conversion from partial to full thickness, graft sites, and acute progression are all relevant.</li>
    <li><strong>Post-discharge photos at intervals</strong> &mdash; weekly for the first month, then monthly. Document scar formation, hypertrophic scarring, pigmentation changes.</li>
    <li><strong>Scar-maturation photos through year 2</strong> &mdash; the final damages picture requires demonstrating scar evolution.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Use consistent lighting and angles. Include a date-stamped object (newspaper, smartphone time display) in the frame. Original files matter; downloaded social-media versions are typically rejected as evidence due to compression and metadata loss.</p>

  <h2>Step 3: Preserve other evidence (within days)</h2>

  <p>Evidence in burn cases disappears quickly. Critical preservation:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>The fire scene</strong> &mdash; for house fires, vehicle fires, and industrial fires, the scene is often substantially altered or demolished within days. Photograph extensively before any cleanup; preserve the fire-investigator report; request preservation by any insurance company involved.</li>
    <li><strong>The defective product</strong> &mdash; for lithium-battery fires, e-cigarette explosions, gas-grill flare-ups, defective appliances. The remains of the product are essential to a product-liability claim. Do not return to the manufacturer (a common request that destroys evidence).</li>
    <li><strong>Surveillance footage</strong> &mdash; restaurant cameras, workplace cameras, parking-lot cameras, and home doorbell cameras have retention windows often as short as 7&ndash;30 days. Request preservation in writing immediately.</li>
    <li><strong>The clothing</strong> &mdash; burned clothing is evidence (synthetic clothing that melts produces different burn patterns than natural fibers; some cases turn on whether protective clothing failed). Do not discard.</li>
    <li><strong>Witness statements</strong> &mdash; bystanders, coworkers, first responders. Names and contact information; brief statements while memory is fresh.</li>
    <li><strong>Police, fire department, and EMS records</strong> &mdash; request copies as soon as available.</li>
    <li><strong>OSHA records</strong> &mdash; for workplace burns, the OSHA log, citations, and equipment maintenance records.</li>
    <li><strong>Product recall information</strong> &mdash; many defective products causing burns have prior recall history. CPSC and NHTSA recall searches are essential.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>An attorney can send "litigation hold" letters to defendants and their insurers immediately, putting them on notice to preserve evidence. The defendants' compliance with these hold letters becomes important if evidence is later "lost."</p>

  <h2>Step 4: Consult a burn-injury attorney (within first 2 weeks)</h2>

  <p>Burn-injury attorneys handle burn cases as a primary specialty &mdash; or at minimum as a substantial subspecialty of catastrophic injury practice. The right attorney has:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Dedicated burn-injury or catastrophic-injury practice (not just general PI).</li>
    <li>Experience with burn life-care planning and reconstructive-surgery expert coordination.</li>
    <li>Track record on similar cases (verifiable through state bar records and verdict databases).</li>
    <li>Resources to litigate complex product-liability or premises cases (often requires $150K+ in case costs).</li>
    <li>Access to specific expert networks &mdash; burn surgeons, fire-cause investigators, life-care planners with burn experience, plastic and reconstructive surgeons.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Most burn-injury firms work on contingency (typically 33&ndash;40% of recovery) with no upfront fees. Initial consultations are free; many will travel to the hospital to meet. The financial commitment is contingent on recovery, so there's no out-of-pocket cost regardless of outcome.</p>

  <p>When interviewing attorneys, ask:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>How many burn cases have you handled in the last 5 years?</li>
    <li>What was your largest burn recovery? Average?</li>
    <li>Who is your typical burn life-care planner and reconstructive-surgery expert?</li>
    <li>How will you identify all potentially liable parties? (For product-liability burns, this often includes manufacturer, distributor, retailer.)</li>
    <li>What's the case timeline you anticipate?</li>
    <li>Who at the firm will I primarily communicate with?</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Step 5: Coordinate insurance immediately</h2>

  <p>Many insurance arrangements may apply to a burn injury:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Health insurance</strong> &mdash; covers acute care, but may push back on extended rehabilitation, out-of-network burn-center transfer, experimental treatments, or psychiatric care.</li>
    <li><strong>Homeowners' or renters' insurance</strong> &mdash; may apply for some accidental burns (e.g., medical-payments coverage on a host's policy after a backyard burn incident).</li>
    <li><strong>Auto insurance</strong> &mdash; for motor-vehicle fires. The injured's own policy and the at-fault driver's liability policy.</li>
    <li><strong>Workers' compensation</strong> &mdash; for workplace burns. Covers medical care and partial wage replacement.</li>
    <li><strong>Premises liability insurance</strong> &mdash; for falls, restaurant scalds, and incidents on someone else's property.</li>
    <li><strong>Product liability coverage</strong> &mdash; for defective-product fires (e-cigarettes, lithium batteries, gas grills, appliances). Manufacturers carry substantial product-liability policies.</li>
    <li><strong>Disability insurance</strong> &mdash; short-term and long-term private policies, plus SSDI.</li>
    <li><strong>Medicaid</strong> &mdash; for those without sufficient private insurance.</li>
    <li><strong>Veterans Affairs</strong> &mdash; for service-connected burn injuries.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Coordinating these is complex. The attorney typically handles coordination once retained. Critical: don't sign anything from any insurance company without attorney review. Quick settlement offers from insurers in the first days post-burn are common and almost always far below the case's actual value.</p>

  <h2>Step 6: Apply for SSDI if disabling</h2>

  <p>Social Security Disability Insurance (SSDI) provides modest monthly income for people unable to work due to disability. Severe burns often qualify, particularly when:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Burns cover &gt;30% TBSA.</li>
    <li>Burns involve hands with significant functional impact.</li>
    <li>Burns involve face/neck with significant disfigurement and functional limitations.</li>
    <li>Burns involve airway with ongoing pulmonary disability.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Benefits typically start 5 months after the onset of disability. Apply as soon as the patient is medically stable. The attorney may help, or refer to a SSDI specialist.</p>

  <h2>Step 7: Plan for the reconstructive-surgery sequence</h2>

  <p>The reconstructive-surgery sequence in severe burns spans years. Family planning includes:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Coordinating with the burn-center plastic/reconstructive team</strong> on the projected procedure list.</li>
    <li><strong>Scheduling around school, work, and family events.</strong> Many procedures require 1&ndash;2 weeks of recovery; some major reconstructive procedures need months.</li>
    <li><strong>Building the reconstructive sequence into the life-care plan.</strong> This becomes the foundation of the future-medical-cost damages claim.</li>
    <li><strong>Managing pressure-garment compliance.</strong> Adherence to pressure-garment wear is critical to scar outcomes and is often documented in the medical record (compliance affects ultimate scar quality and damages).</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Step 8: Family roles and support</h2>

  <p>Burn injury affects the entire family. Practical support that helps:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>One family member coordinates medical communications.</li>
    <li>Another handles insurance paperwork and legal coordination.</li>
    <li>Schedule a regular family meeting to align on decisions.</li>
    <li>Connect with burn-survivor communities (Phoenix Society for Burn Survivors, regional burn-survivor groups). Other patients and families have valuable advice.</li>
    <li>Consider professional family therapy. PTSD, depression, and body-image disorders are common in burn survivors and have ripple effects on family members.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Step 9: Statutes of limitations</h2>

  <p>State-specific deadlines apply. Common timelines:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Personal injury:</strong> 1&ndash;3 years from injury (state-specific). California is 2 years; many states are 2 or 3 years.</li>
    <li><strong>Product liability:</strong> Same as personal injury in most states, but with statute-of-repose limits in some jurisdictions (limiting claims for products older than a certain age).</li>
    <li><strong>Medical malpractice</strong> (for dental, surgical, or radiation burns): Often shorter (1&ndash;3 years) with discovery-rule exceptions; certificate of merit required in some states.</li>
    <li><strong>Workers' compensation:</strong> 30&ndash;90 days for notice to employer; 1&ndash;3 years for claim filing.</li>
    <li><strong>Government defendant:</strong> Special notice rules (often 30&ndash;180 days for tort claim notice).</li>
  </ul>

  <p>An attorney protects all applicable deadlines. The most common failure mode is families waiting too long while focused on recovery, then discovering the deadline has passed.</p>

  <h2>What NOT to do</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Don't sign anything from any insurance company or defendant without an attorney's review.</li>
    <li>Don't return defective products (e-cigarettes, lithium batteries, appliances) to the manufacturer or retailer. They will destroy the evidence.</li>
    <li>Don't dispose of burned clothing or other evidence.</li>
    <li>Don't post about the injury on social media. Anything posted can be used as evidence (defense attorneys monitor social media in catastrophic injury cases). Photos of recovery should be sent to family privately, not posted publicly.</li>
    <li>Don't make recorded statements to insurance adjusters before retaining counsel.</li>
    <li>Don't accept the first settlement offer. Adjusters often make low-ball offers immediately after a burn.</li>
    <li>Don't delay legal consultation. Statutes are running, evidence is disappearing, and the case becomes harder to develop over time.</li>
    <li>Don't refuse psychiatric care or downplay psychological impact. Documented PTSD and depression treatment supports non-economic damages.</li>
  </ul>

